barplot(table(aq$Month), 
  main = "Bar plot of Month", 
  xlab = "Month", 
  ylab = "Frequency", 
  col = "blue")

### Interpretation - The bar plot shows the frequency of each month in the dataset. - The month with the highest frequency is 7, followed by 5 and 8. - The month with the lowest frequency is 6 and 9.

b. Create a histogram of Temp variable and interpret

hist(aq$Temp, 
  main = "Histogram of Temp", 
  xlab = "Temperature", 
  ylab = "Frequency", 
  col = "green"
)

Interpretation, - - The histogram shows the distribution of temperature values in the dataset. - The temperature values are concentrated around 75 to 85 degrees, with a peak around 75 degrees. - The distribution is slightly right-skewed, indicating that there are some higher temperature values. - The histogram has a normal distribution shape, indicating that the temperature values are normally distributed.

#library(tidyverse)
library(tibble)
set.seed(39)
country <- sample(c("USA", "India", "China", "Brazil", "UK"), 20, replace = TRUE)
year <- sample(2000:2020, 20, replace = TRUE)
cases <- sample(1000:10000, 20, replace = TRUE)
population <- sample(1000000:10000000, 20, replace = TRUE)
tibble_data <- tibble(country, year, cases, population)
tibble_data

b. Transform the cases as log of cases(LnCase) and population as log of population(LnPop)

library(dplyr)
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
tibble_data <- tibble_data %>%
  filter(cases > 0, population > 0) %>%  # Remove non-positive values
  mutate(LnCase = log(cases), 
         LnPop = log(population))
